A beispielless future
JERUSALEM – With my nearly 90 years of life, I cannot recall a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
No significant developments of the present were predicted by anyone.
Experts did study the past, but because they were confined within old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Given the dynamic complexity of today's world, where events are more interdependent due to a scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and their leaders is waning. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine its outcome because science and technology know no boundaries.
Global corporations want to pursue their business worldwide, thereby suffering a loss of sovereignty on one hand, but on the other hand weakening racism, prejudices, and significantly nationalism.
Owing to this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. They are more tech-savvy than their parents and are connected to each other through social networks that overcome national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark a struggle of generations rather than a clash of cultures.
The young generation knows that the way states and economies are currently being run is unsuitable for the new times.
However, there are political "jumpers-on" who want to exploit this latest awakening. But it will not be through the further development of a freedom agenda, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, it is primarily Islamist extremists who take up the protests of the younger generation and steal the revolution from them.
Israel positively reacted to the will of the younger generation, but should not intervene in the events of the Arab world.
We are at heart with the rebelling youths and their legitimate yearning for freedom and basic rights, which should allow them to make their voices heard, choose their political leadership, and earn a living.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country is no longer the only democracy in the region, because existing as an island of prosperity amid a sea of poverty is unnatural.
However, there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists will try to win control over less well-organized liberals during elections and thus prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists can offer no real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which also includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only basic reforms of traditional authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example when it comes to achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, because its success is based on the fact that the country had absolutely nothing at the beginning.
When we returned home, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. That is why we have today the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita.
About 95 percent of our agriculture relies on high technology.
We consume less water and yet achieve higher yields per square meter of cultivated area than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also accomplish.
We are ready and willing to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Above all, we must do everything in our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule another people, and that is not its destiny.
We are genuinely interested in the creation of a Palestinian state that exists peacefully alongside democratic Israel, the state of the Jewish people.
Für uns ist Frieden sowohl ein moralischer Imperativ als auch eine nationale Sicherheitsstrategie, denn die Lösung des Konflikts würde helfen, die Region durch Neutralisierung der Extremisten zu stabilisieren, die darauf aus sind, die Bürgerbewegungen zu manipulieren, um ihre radikale Agenda voranzutreiben.
Die internationale Gemeinschaft kann diese Bestrebungen durch Anreize für jene Länder unterstützen, die nach Freiheit und Fortschritt streben.
Gleichzeitig müssen entschiedene und wegweisende politische Maßnahmen gegen die Extremisten ergriffen werden.
Besonders der Iran ist eine Quelle moralischer Verkommenheit, wo man dem Extremismus Vorschub leistet und Reformen blockiert. Man zerschlägt legitime Proteste der eigenen Bürger und arbeitet gegen die tapferen Syrer, die momentan für ihre Freiheit kämpfen.
Außerdem bedient sich der Iran mehrerer Stellvertreter, um Terror gegen moderate Kräfte in der Palästinensischen Behörde, im Libanon und dem Irak anzuzetteln.
Gelingt es dem Iran, sich Atomwaffen anzueignen, könnten die Führer des Landes damit den Nahen und Mittleren Osten erschüttern und noch mehr Extremismus und Gewalt schüren.
Israel wird sich verteidigen, wenn der Iran weiterhin die Zerstörung Israels fordert.
Doch nicht nur Israel ist bedroht. Der Iran ist eine Gefahr für den Frieden und die Stabilität auf der ganzen Welt.
Die Demokratien dieser Welt haben erklärt, dass sie es dem Iran nicht gestatten werden, in den Besitz von Atomwaffen zu gelangen. Es ist ihre Pflicht, diesem Bekenntnis nachzukommen, bevor das nicht mehr möglich ist.
Über diese kurzfristigen Herausforderungen hinaus haben wir alle die Pflicht, die Art und Weise, wie wir unsere Kinder auf den Umgang mit der Welt von heute vorbereiten, grundlegend zu ändern.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to tap into their potential.
Teachers today should motivate our children towards creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free expression of opinion.
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overrated and often restricts the courage that is needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back doesn't make sense.
